CHILE DAYBOOK: Biggest Companies Present at Santiago Conference

-- B y   R a n d y   W o o d s
-- 
2011-05-03T03:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-03/chile-daybook-biggest-companies-present-at-santiago-conference.html
Chile ’s Mining and Energy Minister
 Laurence Golborne  and executives from companies including
retailers SACI Falabella and Cencosud SA, pulp producer Empresas
Copec SA, state-owned copper company Codelco and the country’s
biggest banks will make presentations at the Santander Annual
Investor Summit in Santiago.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*Cia. Sudamericana de Vapores SA,  Latin America ’s largest
container-shipping company, had a first-quarter net loss of $186
million, compared with a loss of $38.4 million a year earlier,
according to a statement posted on the website of Chile’s
securities regulator after the close of trading.
*Empresa Nacional de Telecomunicaciones SA, Chile’s second-
largest mobile telephone operator, reported first-quarter profit
of 52.4 billion pesos after the close of trading.
*The Chilean Association of Investment Fund Administrators gives
presentation at 7:30 a.m. New York time.
*Finance Minister Felipe Larrain and central bank President Jose De Gregorio are scheduled to discuss consumer credit rates with
lower house lawmakers at 3 p.m. New York time in Valparaiso.  EQUITIES:
*The Ipsa index rose 0.1 percent to 4,826.07.
Empresas CMPC SA rose 1 percent to 25,801 pesos. Chile’s second-
largest pulp exporter will invest $1.3 billion in the next two
years, Diario Financiero reported on its website April 29.
*Empresas Iansa SA fell 2.9 percent to 54.47 pesos. Chile’s
largest sugar producer had first quarter net income of $5.36
million, up from $4.36 million. Sale costs rose 79 percent to
$128 million due to higher sugar imports and prices.  MARKETS:
*Chile’s peso retreated from a three-year high after copper
reached a seven-week low as an index of manufacturing declined
in  China , the biggest buyer of Chilean copper. The peso lost 0.4
percent to 462.46 per  U.S. dollar .
*Foreign investors in Chile’s forwards market increased bets
against the peso to $1.7 billion on April 28 from $1.6 billion
on April 27, central bank data show.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
